  "opinion": "As a young woman working as a cleaner in Chicago, I've noticed how stereotype threat lingers in STEM fields even when people try to be careful. Stereotype threat happens when someone's identity—like being a woman in tech—makes them anxious about confirming negative stereotypes, which can actually hurt their performance. I remember when I first tried to take an online coding course last year; I felt my mind go blank during the quiz because I kept thinking, 'What if I'm not good at this?' My parents, one of whom has a PhD, always told me to believe in myself, but sometimes those words feel too abstract when you're standing in a classroom full of people who seem to know everything. The problem isn't just about the stereotypes themselves—it's how they get internalized and how they affect real-life choices. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of just saying 'be confident,' we need to create spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes without judgment. For example, in my workplace, we have a 'no wrong answers' policy for small group problem-solving sessions, and it's helped me feel more comfortable trying things. Addressing stereotype threat requires systemic change: better mentorship programs, inclusive classrooms, and leadership that actively challenges biases. It's not just about fixing individual minds—it's about changing the environment so that everyone can thrive. I'm still struggling with it myself, but I hope that by sharing my experience, others can see that it's okay to be nervous and that we all have the power to create change.",
